I have, for your consideration, a custom one-off Howa 1500 .300 Winchester Magnum ELR rifle for sale. Specs as follows:

Howa 1500 action (trued)
Krieger #10 MTU barrel with a 1:10" twist, 4 groove, finished at 26" from the bolt face
McMillan A5 stock with adjustable length of pull spacers, saddle cheek piece, two flush cups on the left side and one bipod stud on bottom; Devcon bedded with aluminum pillars
CDI Precision detachable bottom metal with 1 AICS 5 round magazine(bedded to stock)
EGW one piece 20 moa base
Factory trigger

I haven't fired it very much, maybe 200 rounds of factory 220 grain match and 180 hunting ammo. I'm not a group shooter, so I don't have any groups to post, but I will tell you that I was consistently decimating small cans of Barbasol at 450 yards the last time I took this rifle out. It does not have a muzzle break like you see on a lot of magnums, but at roughly 13 pounds the weight offsets the recoil. Also, in the interest of full disclosure, it isn't a safe queen. There are a couple small dings in the stock (purely cosmetic), and I painted it in Krylon because I can never seem to decide what color I want. It is easily removable however, because I kept the paint off of the bolt and out of the action.

I need to move this soon as school priorities are taking over, so I am looking for $2200 or best offer. Cash is king, as well as local sales. If local, I will require a valid OKDL or CCW and a bill of sale. I will entertain trades, however it will only be for a factory Remington 700 (.308) AAC-SD, 5R milspec or SPS Tactical (1:10" tw) plus cash. Thank you for looking!

Also, the pictures are of the rifle fully kitted as it sits at the moment, however the sale will NOT include the scope, bipod, sling or stock pack.

Radom Vis 35 pistol all matching serial numbers with one original magazine. This unique  9mm pistol produced during World War 2 under German occupation. title: For Sale:  Old West Rossi "Overland" 20-gauge side by side coachgun/shotgun
postcontent:
Beautiful Amadeo Rossi “Overland” model 20 gauge side by side/double-barrel coachman shotgun. These were produced in Brazil, South America in the mid-1970s and 1980s. This one has an eighteen-inch barrel and 3-inch chamber and will take will hold/fire 2 ¾ or 3-inch shells/slugs. It has a separate trigger for each side of the barrel. Wood finish is in excellent condition. The barrel is in excellent shape save a few very minor rub marks. Note: There is no safety on this model. 

I’ve owned this for just a few months. I purchased it as a potential home protection weapon, which it is indeed a good one, however it makes my wife way too nervous to leave it sitting out, and when children visit the house I have no place to stash the gun save my vehicle or loft, which is a pain. 

I've added a nice five-shell ammo butt sleeve to the shotgun (included), and will also include a partial box of bird shot, and 4-5 #3 buckshot shells.  

I’ve decided to stick to my easy to hide pistols for home protection. My loss is someone else’s gain to own this pretty piece Old West arsenal history for protection, game hunting, or if you’re good, skeet shooting. 

Photos available upon request. At time of sail, buyer/seller will agree on a delivery location. Buyer must agree to provide a valid Washington state driver’s license, and agree to sign a bill of sale.

title: For Sale:   Madson -- 30.06 Cal Bolt Action Miltary Rifle Very good/
postcontent: Estate rifle Madson miltary rifle 30.06 rifle in very good condition comes with sling. must transfer with 01 or 03 license. Columbian Madsen Rifle Collection 30-06 This auction is for Columbian Military Rifles chambered in .30-06. This semi auto is the rarest with only around 5000 being made for Columbia. It is in very good condition and has all the visible numbers matching. The Madsen bolt action is another unusual military rifle. It was produced at a time when most militaries were moving to semi auto rifle and only around 5000 of these were manufactured. It is in very good condition. The barrel has an early form of "scout sights" and even has an intergal muzzle brake of unusual design. The butt plates on both these rifles are soft rubber. Here is a chance to enjoy a unique and hard-to-find Columbian rifles. Please email any questions or requests for additional, detailed pictures that you wish to see. In cardboard box to protect them. Firearms without original boxes are most often shipped in new hard cases. On rare occasions, we ship in well packaged and protected soft cases. We try our best to make sure that there is no damage in shipping and request that you contact us immediately if any is discovered. Normal shipping methods isUSPS. You will be notified with a tracking number when your package has been shipped. Please make sure that this item is legal in your state before bidding. The easiest way to verify the legality of a firearm is to check with your local FFL transfer dealer that you use. They will immediately know if the item is legal in your area and they are most often glad to help as they will receive the benefit of your transfer fee. Non-firearm items can be very confusing as to local laws. We use the guidelines establish by several large sporting goods mail order companies. We have no desire to break any local, state, or federal laws as we know no one would intentionally do this. We do reserve the right to cancel a bid and not ship an item to the winning bidder if we find it is illegal to ship to that locality or if it is a "gray area" of legality. We would to this only to protect the buyer as well as us against any civil or criminal violations and greatly appreciate. I'll let pictures tell the story, and provide links to info about these rifles, but essentially, the Danish Madsen was the last Military bolt action rifle produced, and due to it being produced after WW2, it actually never saw any military use, and was only stored by the Columbians who were the only country to place an order for the rifles. After storage, they were sold surplus to the USA, and are found only on the second hand market now. They are chambered in .30 cal(30-06) for the american M2 ball ammunition, which is why i picked it up, as i have several U.S. rifle already in 30-06, as well as a supply of M2 ball ammo to feed this rifle and others. THey have an integrated muzzlebreak, and adjustable peep sights as original equipment. This rifle is in original condition, and not sporterized in any way. Estimates place the total quantity of these rifles made at less than 6500 total, since columbia never accepted the contract with Madsen, no more were ever made, so these rifles are a cool piece of C&R military history. Columbia never accepted the contract due to the U.S. loan/leasing them a stockpile of semi-auto M1 Garands and Carbines after WW2, not due to any flaws with the madsen, it's just that the bolt-action rifle's day had passed and semi-auto's were the new norm THANKS FOR THE INTEREST AND HAPPY BIDDING!!!

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson M&P 9 ( M p 9) CUSTOM
postcontent:
Up for sale is a Smith & Wesson m&p 9 that was completely customized by a professional and certified gunsmith.

This pistol has been completely reworked, and shoots amazingly.

The Slide:
The slide has lightening holes cut into it on the sides and the top. The recess on both sides of the slide have also been milled for a more pronounced look, and to shave off a touch more weight. Front cocking serrations have also been added to the end of the slide. The barrel has been polished, and the slide is finished off in Cerakote Burnt Bronze.

The Frame:
The frame has had the entire trigger guard reworked for more comfortable handling. The trigger guard has also undercut for a higher grip purchase. The frame has been stippled for a more rock solid grip with sweaty hands as well. The frame has been finished in Cerakote Coyote Tan.

Internally:
Trigger job has been done for reduced pull and overtravel. Breaks cleanly and crisp at 4.25 lbs every time. Also has a Wolff steel recoil guide rod and 20 lb recoil spring. 

The pistol comes with three magazines, the box, and all the factory paperwork etc. 
2 magazines are 17 rounds mags, and 1 is a 17 round with an Arredondo base plate for a total capacity of 22 rounds.

This is not a "BIG NAME" build like those pistols you see selling for $2500 and up, but this is as close as you'll get without having to spend that much money. This gun shoots flawlessly and accurately, and eats anything. You will not be disappointed.

Not interested in trades, only want to sell. 

Call or text 270-893-8 SEVEN 8 NINE.

$1300 obo. This price does not include the Streamlight TLR-2s weapon light. But if you want it, I'll let it go for $200 if you buy the pistol.

title: For Sale:  SOLD - Colt Commando Special edition (198x)
postcontent:
As a limited production sub model of the Colt Detective Special revolver, this mid eighties variant was only produced from 1984-1986. 

Outside of the limited two year production run, what distinguished this version and set it apart at the time was was the matte black finish and Colt medallion branded rubber grips. 

Chambered in .38 special, weighing 21.5 oz., and out of production for 28 years, nice examples of the Colt Commando Special are becoming increasingly difficult to acquire. 

The example being offered here is in very good/excellent condition, with but one small finish streak on the cylinder (see photos). It was purchased new by the current owner and comes with all original packaging and materials from Colt. 

Considering the fine condition of this example and the limited availability of this edition, it is priced extremely competitively at 750.00. Out right purchase (or will consider trades involving Seecamp .32 cal. only.)

title: For Sale:  Antique Cannon --- Desk Top Percussion Cap Black Powder Mortar
location: Historic Hampton, VA, Hampton Roads, Virginia
postcontent:
Where do I post an antique, working cannon?

Antique Cannon – High Quality

High quality and fully functional miniature known as a “desk top cannon”

This thing is old and I will describe it with what I know and what I think.  If you have expertise and/or experience and can tell me more … please do.  Email me.

I found this in an estate buried in stuff.  The patina in the wood and the age (with surface rust) of the iron confirms its age.  All I did to clean it up was to scrub it with a rag because I did not want to impact the patina.

The cannon base measures    and the barrel is … long.  The end of the tube is about …
I have fired it and it works well; perhaps too well.  Once, I loaded it (and even put less of a charge in it) and pointed it out into the harbor/river across from my house … thinking the projectile would land in the water.  It actually went over the river/harbor and disappeared over the other side.

The caps and the nipple were interesting to figure out.  Part of the reason that I think it is REALLY OLD is the nipple.  They come in sizes and this is the larger size.  I tried to find a smaller (modern cap) nipple that would fit, and they do not exist.  I investigated getting a machine shop to make a modern sized nipple that would fit, but failed.  Eventually, I found a web site that led to the one company that still makes these nipples, which are intended for Civil War re-enactors with Civil War era weapons.  They use this size (which I learned while looking at weapons at Gettysburg).  I purchased all of those caps that I could … AND THEY WORK GREAT.  Apparently, the previous owner was shooting large marbles.

The other interesting part is the engraved plate that is on it.  It is hard to read (and harder to photograph) but it's there and you can make it out.

Pretty cool.  Prefer cash FTF but will ship after payment.  This is not a "gun" so can mail.  Shipping in the 48 included in sales price. 

I love to play with it, but it's gotta go.   Make an offer.

I'm only trying to cash-out so no trades ... unless you have a Beowulf.
